# Netlify Create Setup

This package is the version to use when you want Netlify Create / Visual Editor.

## Important

Netlify Create requires the site to be connected through GitHub or another Git provider. The plain drag-and-drop static upload can publish the website, but it cannot provide a full Git-backed Visual Editor workflow.

## What Is Included

- `stackbit.config.ts` at the project root
- Git CMS content source for the `content/` directory
- Editable models for:
  - Home page copy
  - Music releases
  - Merch catalog
  - Motion Wall prompts
  - Site settings and links
  - Manifesto page
- Netlify build settings in `netlify.toml`
- Next.js preview command for the editor

## GitHub Upload

1. Create a new GitHub repository.
2. Upload the contents of this folder to that repository.
3. Do not upload `node_modules` or `.next` if they exist locally.

## Netlify Deploy Settings

When importing the GitHub repo into Netlify, use:

```text
Build command: pnpm build
Publish directory: .next
```

The `netlify.toml` file already contains these settings.

## Enable Netlify Create / Visual Editor

1. In Netlify, open the deployed site.
2. Go to **Project configuration**.
3. Open **Visual Editor**.
4. Set up the preview environment.
5. Netlify should detect `stackbit.config.ts`.
6. Connect your GitHub account as the content source when prompted.
7. Restart the preview environment after the first setup.

After setup, edits made in Netlify Create can write back to the structured files in the GitHub repo.

[build]
  command = "pnpm build"
  publish = ".next"

[[plugins]]
  package = "@netlify/plugin-nextjs"

[dev]
  command = "pnpm dev"
  port = 3000

[context.production.environment]
  NEXT_PUBLIC_ENABLE_WALL = "true"

/// <reference types="next" />
/// <reference types="next/image-types/global" />
/// <reference path="./.next/types/routes.d.ts" />

// NOTE: This file should not be edited
// see https://nextjs.org/docs/app/api-reference/config/typescript for more information.

import type { NextConfig } from "next";

const nextConfig: NextConfig = {
  images: {
    remotePatterns: [
      {
        protocol: "https",
        hostname: "**"
      }
    ]
  }
};

export default nextConfig;

